01:22:27.502 --> 01:22:30.002
remains a disease with high unmet medical need.

1413
01:22:30.882 --> 01:22:34.722
In the US alone, there are over 20,000 new cases per year, and the

1414
01:22:34.742 --> 01:22:38.702
disease has a fairly low five-year survival rate with a particularly

1415
01:22:38.742 --> 01:22:42.412
poor prognosis for patients in the relapse refractory disease setting.

1416
01:22:43.502 --> 01:22:47.262
Available treatments involve conventional chemotherapy, hypomethylating

1417
01:22:47.382 --> 01:22:49.562
agents, and small molecule inhibitors.

1418
01:22:50.042 --> 01:22:53.942
And while these treatments have improved overall survival, patients can still

1419
01:22:53.982 --> 01:22:57.422
remain largely incurable. And unfortunately,

1420
01:22:57.482 --> 01:23:01.111
antibody-based therapies for AML have been largely

1421
01:23:01.482 --> 01:23:05.102
impaired or limited due to a lack of tumor-specific surface

1422
01:23:05.142 --> 01:23:08.822
targets. And so there's really a need for potent therapies

1423
01:23:08.862 --> 01:23:11.422
against novel tumor-selective targets in AML.

1424
01:23:12.982 --> 01:23:16.922
And we believe one such target is a peptide from the cathepsin G protein,

1425
01:23:17.022 --> 01:23:20.622
which we had a nice preview of a couple of talks ago.

1426
01:23:20.942 --> 01:23:24.611
Cathepsin G is a serine protease that's restricted to the myeloid

1427
01:23:24.662 --> 01:23:28.542
lineage. It's predominantly found in neutrophils, and it plays

1428
01:23:28.602 --> 01:23:31.162
a role in the inflammatory response to pathogens.

1429
01:23:31.842 --> 01:23:34.962
However, within AML, it is overexpressed.

1430
01:23:35.462 --> 01:23:39.382
Cathepsin G has been shown to be upregulated in primary AML blasts

1431
01:23:39.822 --> 01:23:42.182
and overexpressed in leukemic stem cells.

1432
01:23:42.611 --> 01:23:46.382
And it's also been shown to be mislocalized to the cytoplasm of these AML

1433
01:23:46.422 --> 01:23:50.342
cells, allowing for these cells to present cathepsin G peptides

1434
01:23:50.402 --> 01:23:51.762
on HLA molecules.

1435
01:23:52.942 --> 01:23:56.642
And the particular peptide that we're interested in, CG1, is a

1436
01:23:56.702 --> 01:23:59.972
nine-mer peptide presented on HLA-0201.

1437
01:24:00.902 --> 01:24:04.712
HLA-0201 is found in about 40% of the US population,

1438
01:24:05.222 --> 01:24:08.972
and the peptide CG1 has been widely identified via mass

1439
01:24:09.062 --> 01:24:12.242
spec in patients across different AML subtypes.

1440
01:24:13.042 --> 01:24:15.142
And so given its prevalence in AML,

1441
01:24:15.982 --> 01:24:19.562
we've developed CVX250, which is a TCR mimetic

1442
01:24:19.602 --> 01:24:23.442
bispecific T cell engager that targets the CG1 peptide

1443
01:24:23.462 --> 01:24:27.042
presented on HLA-0201 and engages CD3.

1444
01:24:29.182 --> 01:24:33.082
We've previously shown that CVX250 mediates potent killing of

1445
01:24:33.102 --> 01:24:36.942
leukemic cells in vitro. On the left, I'm showing you in vitro

1446
01:24:37.002 --> 01:24:40.822
cytotoxicity data of four different AML cell lines with

1447
01:24:40.862 --> 01:24:44.732
different predicted CG1 peptide HLA copy numbers, as shown in

1448
01:24:44.762 --> 01:24:46.422
the parentheses for each cell line.

1449
01:24:47.282 --> 01:24:51.272
We're looking at the concentration of CVX250 on the x-axis with

1450
01:24:51.282 --> 01:24:53.822
percent cytotoxicity on the y-axis.

1451
01:24:54.372 --> 01:24:57.882
And for all four cell lines, you can see potent T cell-mediated

1452
01:24:57.982 --> 01:25:01.662
killing of these leukemic cells with single-digit picomolar

1453
01:25:01.742 --> 01:25:05.662
EC50 values and sub-nanomolar EC90 values across

1454
01:25:05.682 --> 01:25:06.842
all these four cell lines.

1455
01:25:08.722 --> 01:25:12.482
We've also previously shown that CVX250 mediates potent in vivo

1456
01:25:12.542 --> 01:25:14.762
control in an AML CDX model.

1457
01:25:15.702 --> 01:25:19.402
Here we use NSG mice that have human PBMCs

1458
01:25:19.462 --> 01:25:23.422
introduced to them and have been implanted with the ML2 AML cell

1459
01:25:23.482 --> 01:25:27.182
line. When we treat these mice with one of three concentrations of

1460
01:25:27.222 --> 01:25:31.082
CVX250, we observe potent tumor control

1461
01:25:31.502 --> 01:25:35.042
driven by CVX250, specifically in comparison to the

1462
01:25:35.062 --> 01:25:37.822
control T cell engager as shown on the left.

1463
01:25:38.722 --> 01:25:42.052
And so we've wanted to build upon these data and to really

1464
01:25:42.062 --> 01:25:45.722
determine what the minimum CG1 peptide HLA copy

1465
01:25:45.782 --> 01:25:49.632
number was in order for CVX250 to remain effective.

1466
01:25:50.182 --> 01:25:53.442
And to do this, we used a panel of U937 cell

1467
01:25:53.462 --> 01:25:57.322
lines that have different predicted CG1 peptide HLA copy

1468
01:25:57.382 --> 01:25:58.732
numbers on their surface.

1469
01:25:59.582 --> 01:26:03.272
These cell lines were developed by our collaborators at MD Anderson and

1470
01:26:03.282 --> 01:26:07.002
really span the range of predicted CG1 peptide HLA

1471
01:26:07.042 --> 01:26:10.982
copy numbers, ranging from 15 predicted copies per cell all the way

1472
01:26:11.062 --> 01:26:14.910
up to almost 8,000 copies per cell.When we

1473
01:26:14.950 --> 01:26:17.430
evaluate these cell lines in a cytotoxicity

1474
01:26:19.110 --> 01:26:22.310
assay, you can see that we observe comparable levels of

1475
01:26:22.350 --> 01:26:26.010
cytotoxicity and EC50 values with cell lines that have

1476
01:26:26.070 --> 01:26:29.930
383 copies per cell all the way up to almost 8,000

1477
01:26:29.990 --> 01:26:33.790
copies per cell. And we even observe robust killing of the cell

1478
01:26:33.830 --> 01:26:37.020
line that has 33 copies per cell, suggesting that

1479
01:26:37.050 --> 01:26:41.010
CBX250 is really able to mediate potent killing even at these

1480
01:26:41.070 --> 01:26:42.370
low target densities.

1481
01:26:44.850 --> 01:26:48.670
So tumor cell heterogeneity is a challenge for many indications,

1482
01:26:48.730 --> 01:26:52.090
including AML, particularly within the bone marrow

1483
01:26:52.150 --> 01:26:55.610
microenvironment. And so we wanted to evaluate whether or not

1484
01:26:55.650 --> 01:26:59.590
CBX250 could mediate bystander killing, which is a recognized

1485
01:26:59.630 --> 01:27:03.530
feature of T-cell engagers and is the way in which target-negative cancer

1486
01:27:03.570 --> 01:27:04.670
cells can be killed.

1487
01:27:05.570 --> 01:27:09.370
The way this works is CBX250-activated T-cells are

1488
01:27:09.450 --> 01:27:12.340
able to potently kill target-positive cells.

1489
01:27:12.990 --> 01:27:16.830
When this happens, these activated T-cells can upregulate various surface

1490
01:27:16.930 --> 01:27:20.430
markers like FAS ligand and LFA-1 and can

1491
01:27:20.450 --> 01:27:23.850
secrete cytokines like interferon gamma and TNF alpha.

1492
01:27:24.850 --> 01:27:28.350
These cytokines can act on nearby target-negative cancer cells,

1493
01:27:28.590 --> 01:27:32.140
inducing the upregulation of FAS and ICAM-1.

1494
01:27:32.150 --> 01:27:36.060
And through the interactions on the surface of these cells with the target-negative

1495
01:27:36.130 --> 01:27:39.950
cancer cells and the activated T-cells, the activated T-cells are able

1496
01:27:40.010 --> 01:27:42.160
to kill these target-negative cancer cells.

1497
01:27:43.490 --> 01:27:47.410
And so in order to determine if CBX250 could mediate bystander

1498
01:27:47.490 --> 01:27:51.470
killing, we co-cultured a mixture of target-positive cancer

1499
01:27:51.550 --> 01:27:55.450
cells and target-negative cancer cells with donor T-cells and evaluated

1500
01:27:55.460 --> 01:27:58.430
the cytotoxicity of both of these cell lines in vitro.

1501
01:27:59.590 --> 01:28:03.250
The ratio of target-positive to target-negative cells ranged from

1502
01:28:03.330 --> 01:28:06.810
100% target positive all the way down to 0% target

1503
01:28:06.890 --> 01:28:07.410
positive.

1504
01:28:08.290 --> 01:28:11.940
On the left, I'm showing you the cytotoxicity data from the target-positive

1505
01:28:12.010 --> 01:28:14.690
cells, which is consistent with what we've seen before.

1506
01:28:14.810 --> 01:28:18.590
We see nice dose-dependent cytotoxicity of these target-positive

1507
01:28:18.670 --> 01:28:21.410
cells driven by CBX250.

1508
01:28:22.270 --> 01:28:26.099
And on the right, when we look at the cytotoxicity of the target-negative cells,

1509
01:28:26.410 --> 01:28:27.650
we actually observe

1510
01:28:28.450 --> 01:28:32.240
nice dose-dependent increases in cytotoxicity of these target-negative

1511
01:28:32.330 --> 01:28:35.790
cells only when the target-positive cells are present,

1512
01:28:35.990 --> 01:28:39.690
suggesting that CBX250 is able to mediate bystander killing.

1513
01:28:42.170 --> 01:28:45.690
We also wanted to build upon our safety data and to determine whether or not

1514
01:28:45.730 --> 01:28:49.300
CBX250 could induce any cytokine release in healthy donor whole

1515
01:28:49.390 --> 01:28:53.230
blood. To do this, we evaluated eight different cytokines

1516
01:28:53.350 --> 01:28:57.270
following incubation of soluble CBX250 across five

1517
01:28:57.330 --> 01:29:00.590
concentrations, and we found no meaningful cytokine

1518
01:29:00.630 --> 01:29:03.970
induction of CBX250, specifically in

1519
01:29:04.030 --> 01:29:07.810
comparison to our two positive controls shown in red and orange.

1520
01:29:09.990 --> 01:29:13.950
To further evaluate the safety of our molecule, we wanted to determine whether or

1521
01:29:13.970 --> 01:29:16.450
not platelets are activated by CBX250.

1522
01:29:17.190 --> 01:29:20.870
So although platelets likely don't express CG1 peptide, they can

1523
01:29:20.910 --> 01:29:24.530
express high levels of class I HLA and therefore may be

1524
01:29:24.570 --> 01:29:28.350
targets for potential cross-reactivity against CBX250.

1525
01:29:29.670 --> 01:29:33.110
So to evaluate this, we cultured platelets with

1526
01:29:33.150 --> 01:29:36.650
CBX250 and then evaluated platelet activation using a flow

1527
01:29:36.690 --> 01:29:40.170
cytometry-based readout, specifically looking at P-selectin

1528
01:29:40.230 --> 01:29:42.950
expression, which is a marker for platelet activation.

1529
01:29:44.890 --> 01:29:48.330
In the middle, I'm showing you the results of the positive control, CRP.

1530
01:29:48.850 --> 01:29:52.190
We observe a really nice dose-dependent increase in P-selectin

1531
01:29:52.250 --> 01:29:55.970
expression as we increase CRP concentration.

1532
01:29:55.990 --> 01:29:59.750
Whereas on the right, when we evaluate P-selectin expression following

1533
01:29:59.850 --> 01:30:03.810
CBX250 incubation, we don't observe any increases in

1534
01:30:03.850 --> 01:30:07.650
P-selectin expression, suggesting that platelets are not

1535
01:30:07.730 --> 01:30:09.470
activated by CBX250.

1536
01:30:11.970 --> 01:30:15.790
We also wanted to evaluate the specificity of our molecule by screening its

1537
01:30:15.830 --> 01:30:19.629
binding across a library of over 6,500 human proteins.

1538
01:30:20.310 --> 01:30:24.150
This is a platform developed by Retrogenix and is widely utilized to

1539
01:30:24.190 --> 01:30:26.470
evaluate off-target binding interactions.

1540
01:30:27.170 --> 01:30:30.949
So we evaluated CBX250 using this platform at a high

1541
01:30:31.009 --> 01:30:34.290
concentration, and we found no significant specific

1542
01:30:34.390 --> 01:30:38.310
interactions detected with any of the human proteins evaluated, with

1543
01:30:38.350 --> 01:30:42.280
the exception of two, one of which was CD3, which is, of course, one

1544
01:30:42.310 --> 01:30:45.970
of the primary targets of CBX250, and the other was

1545
01:30:46.070 --> 01:30:47.090
FcGR2A.

1546
01:30:47.930 --> 01:30:51.430
So we believe that this interaction between CBX250 and

1547
01:30:51.550 --> 01:30:55.110
FcGR2A likely occurs through the FC domain of our

1548
01:30:55.130 --> 01:30:58.690
molecule, which contains the clinically validated silencing

1549
01:30:58.750 --> 01:31:02.570
mutation Lala KA. And while this mutation greatly

1550
01:31:02.610 --> 01:31:06.190
reduces binding to the FC gamma receptors, it doesn't completely

1551
01:31:06.230 --> 01:31:10.110
eliminate it. And we believe that this interaction was observed likely due

1552
01:31:10.150 --> 01:31:14.070
to the high concentrations of CBX250 tested using this

1553
01:31:14.090 --> 01:31:14.690
platform.

1554
01:31:16.490 --> 01:31:20.430
And so finally, we wanted to evaluate the pharmacology of our molecule by

1555
01:31:20.470 --> 01:31:24.410
assessing serum pharmacokinetics in naive male monkeys following a

1556
01:31:24.450 --> 01:31:28.170
single ascending dose. The PK profile for IV

1557
01:31:28.210 --> 01:31:32.190
administration on the left and subcutaneous administration on the

1558
01:31:32.290 --> 01:31:35.950
right were consistent with IgG-like molecules with a

1559
01:31:35.990 --> 01:31:38.950
half-life ranging from seven to 14 days for IV

1560
01:31:38.990 --> 01:31:42.430
administration and eight to 12 days for subcutaneous

1561
01:31:42.470 --> 01:31:43.790
administration.

1562
01:31:45.550 --> 01:31:49.010
So overall, we've shown that CBX250 has potent in

1563
01:31:49.050 --> 01:31:52.650
vitro killing capabilities. It's able to target

1564
01:31:53.450 --> 01:31:57.080
cell lines with very low target copy numbers, as low as

1565
01:31:57.190 --> 01:32:01.170
33 copies per cell, and is capable of inducing bystander killing.

1566
01:32:02.130 --> 01:32:05.990
We've shown that CBX250 displays a strong safety profile with limited

1567
01:32:06.070 --> 01:32:09.800
cytokine release in whole blood and no impact on platelet activation,

1568
01:32:10.650 --> 01:32:14.150
and that it's highly specific to its targets with no significant off-target

1569
01:32:14.210 --> 01:32:17.530
interactions found after screening over 6,500 human

1570
01:32:17.590 --> 01:32:20.890
proteins. And lastly, that CBX250 has an

1571
01:32:20.950 --> 01:32:24.830
IgG-like half-life and PK profile with minimal immunogenicity

1572
01:32:24.970 --> 01:32:28.914
risks in data that I didn't have time to share with you today.And so taken

1573
01:32:28.974 --> 01:32:32.954
together, these data support the clinical development of CBX 250 and a

1574
01:32:32.974 --> 01:32:34.834
phase one trial is currently underway.

1575
01:32:35.574 --> 01:32:38.574
So thank you for your attention, and I'd be happy to take any questions.

1576
01:32:42.374 --> 01:32:46.234
Thanks so much for a clear presentation.

1577
01:32:46.294 --> 01:32:47.674
We have time for a couple questions.

1578
01:32:49.194 --> 01:32:50.694
I have one question. Very nice.

1579
01:32:51.514 --> 01:32:54.534
So some AMLs actually apparently express FCR2A.

1580
01:32:54.694 --> 01:32:58.274
Have you guys looked whether that engagement of like even if it's minimal of the

1581
01:32:58.334 --> 01:33:01.014
molecule, could modulate some of the activity?

1582
01:33:01.894 --> 01:33:02.754
Could you repeat that? Sorry.

1583
01:33:02.834 --> 01:33:05.774
So FCR2A can be expressed on AML.

1584
01:33:06.614 --> 01:33:06.854
Mm.

1585
01:33:06.934 --> 01:33:10.694
So the question is that even if it's a minimal engagement of the FC

1586
01:33:10.703 --> 01:33:14.454
portion, do you think that can potentially contribute to the activity or

1587
01:33:14.514 --> 01:33:15.734
aggregate the activity in any way?

1588
01:33:16.234 --> 01:33:17.054
Yeah. So,

1589
01:33:18.334 --> 01:33:22.074
I would say we're pretty confident that it's actually not going to be engaging

1590
01:33:22.194 --> 01:33:23.094
FCGR2A,

1591
01:33:23.994 --> 01:33:26.934
just based on some follow-up octet studies that we've done.

1592
01:33:27.534 --> 01:33:30.594
But it does sound like, I guess from what you're saying, that it could also be

1593
01:33:30.634 --> 01:33:34.574
beneficial should that be the case, if I'm understanding your question

1594
01:33:34.614 --> 01:33:34.974
correctly.

1595
01:33:35.934 --> 01:33:37.044
Something that could be monitored.

1596
01:33:37.334 --> 01:33:39.834
Yes, for sure. Something that can definitely be monitored.

1597
01:33:39.894 --> 01:33:40.834
I'm curious about

1598
01:33:41.714 --> 01:33:45.234
sort of uniformity of antigen expression.

1599
01:33:45.244 --> 01:33:48.014
So with Tebentafusp that we use with uveal melanoma,

1600
01:33:49.574 --> 01:33:53.414
the HMB45, the GP100 is so

1601
01:33:53.454 --> 01:33:57.374
highly and uniformly expressed in those tumors, and that's thought to be

1602
01:33:57.414 --> 01:34:00.434
part of the mechanism of efficacy.

1603
01:34:01.014 --> 01:34:01.614
And so

1604
01:34:02.434 --> 01:34:06.414
I'm a little bit curious about whether the mechanism of tumor cell

1605
01:34:06.494 --> 01:34:10.234
killing is different in vivo than in vitro, and if you won't pick up the

1606
01:34:10.254 --> 01:34:12.494
bystander killing in real patients.

1607
01:34:12.514 --> 01:34:15.254
Yeah. So that's something we'll certainly have to wait and see.

1608
01:34:15.534 --> 01:34:19.414
I think we're very encouraged by at least the preclinical data showing

1609
01:34:19.454 --> 01:34:23.314
that we're able to target those low copy number cells and able to induce

1610
01:34:23.334 --> 01:34:27.294
bystander killing. I think unfortunately we won't have the answer to

1611
01:34:27.334 --> 01:34:30.944
that until we see the clinical efficacy, but I think

1612
01:34:31.034 --> 01:34:34.814
overall our preclinical data suggests that hopefully we'll be able to

1613
01:34:34.834 --> 01:34:35.934
mediate some of those effects.

1614
01:34:36.394 --> 01:34:37.593
There's a question over here on our right.

1615
01:34:38.214 --> 01:34:40.294
I have two questions.

1616
01:34:40.354 --> 01:34:41.574
Just one. We have time for one.

1617
01:34:41.823 --> 01:34:42.134
Okay.

1618
01:34:42.234 --> 01:34:43.074
So prioritize.

1619
01:34:43.274 --> 01:34:45.774
Right. So, in the clinical trial,

1620
01:34:46.954 --> 01:34:50.274
do you need to screen the patients based on the CG1

1621
01:34:50.854 --> 01:34:51.274
presence?

1622
01:34:51.994 --> 01:34:55.454
So, we're planning on doing that retrospectively.

1623
01:34:55.654 --> 01:34:55.674
Oh.

1624
01:34:55.714 --> 01:34:59.674
So right now we're just enrolling patients that have HLA-0201

1625
01:34:59.774 --> 01:35:02.894
positivity, and then retrospectively we'll look for-

1626
01:35:03.114 --> 01:35:03.714
I see

1627
01:35:03.723 --> 01:35:04.184
... the CG1,

1628
01:35:05.114 --> 01:35:06.634
and cathepsin D expression.

1629
01:35:07.014 --> 01:35:08.394
So as long as they're

1630
01:35:09.554 --> 01:35:11.814
0201 positive, they're enrolled, right?

1631
01:35:12.094 --> 01:35:12.334
Yes.

1632
01:35:12.494 --> 01:35:13.014
Okay. Thank you.

1633
01:35:13.674 --> 01:35:15.214
Okay. Thanks for a great presentation.

1634
01:35:18.694 --> 01:35:19.134
All right.

1635
01:35:20.094 --> 01:35:23.974
Last presentation, Gastrointestinal Tumor Associated

1636
01:35:24.294 --> 01:35:27.194
Target: A First-in-Class Therapeutic Monoclonal Antibody by Dr.

1637
01:35:27.614 --> 01:35:28.474
Jenny Go.

1638
01:35:33.494 --> 01:35:33.714
Hi.

1639
01:35:34.934 --> 01:35:35.614
Good afternoon.

1640
01:35:38.654 --> 01:35:42.174
So thank you very much for this opportunity to be part of such a

1641
01:35:42.234 --> 01:35:46.034
great session. I do believe this is the last talk, so

1642
01:35:46.074 --> 01:35:48.094
hopefully I can keep you interested till the end.

1643
01:35:48.974 --> 01:35:52.534
My name is Jenny Go, and I'm here on behalf of my

1644
01:35:52.594 --> 01:35:55.134
team called Resers Therapeutics.

1645
01:35:55.514 --> 01:35:59.254
We are a small biotech startup located in

1646
01:35:59.314 --> 01:36:03.274
Seoul, South Korea. And our main mission is to develop

1647
01:36:03.294 --> 01:36:07.094
novel solutions for cancers, especially those that do not

1648
01:36:07.134 --> 01:36:09.364
respond well to current immunotherapy.

1649
01:36:10.094 --> 01:36:14.014
And so today I will present our early preclinical work on a

1650
01:36:14.054 --> 01:36:17.974
first-in-class monoclonal antibody targeting a membrane

1651
01:36:18.034 --> 01:36:21.094
protein highly expressed in gastrointestinal cancers.

1652
01:36:22.034 --> 01:36:24.443
This is my disclosure information.

1653
01:36:26.134 --> 01:36:30.034
Okay, so let's get started with a very well-known medical unmet need.

1654
01:36:30.914 --> 01:36:34.163
Immunotherapy has greatly improved... Oh, is it?

1655
01:36:34.534 --> 01:36:35.414
Sorry, not

1656
01:36:36.274 --> 01:36:36.574
going on.

1657
01:36:36.754 --> 01:36:37.464
Use the clicker.

1658
01:36:37.874 --> 01:36:38.554
Ah, okay.

1659
01:36:39.934 --> 01:36:40.094
So

1660
01:36:41.874 --> 01:36:45.763
immunotherapy has greatly improved survival outcomes in

1661
01:36:45.814 --> 01:36:49.654
many cancers. However, while it is a miracle drug

1662
01:36:49.693 --> 01:36:53.574
for those who respond, the percentage of patients who

1663
01:36:53.834 --> 01:36:57.814
do respond is still quite low, especially in tumors such as

1664
01:36:57.974 --> 01:37:01.894
MSS-CRC and pancreatic cancer, which show virtually no

1665
01:37:01.974 --> 01:37:04.684
response to immune checkpoint blockade.

1666
01:37:05.694 --> 01:37:09.554
And this is largely due to the fact that these cancers have an

1667
01:37:09.614 --> 01:37:13.514
immune excluded TME, where effector T cells

1668
01:37:13.694 --> 01:37:16.974
fail to infiltrate the tumor, and NK cells are largely

1669
01:37:17.014 --> 01:37:17.774
dysfunctional.

1670
01:37:18.774 --> 01:37:22.434
And this results in response rates for such cancers

1671
01:37:23.154 --> 01:37:24.734
around the 20% mark,

1672
01:37:26.254 --> 01:37:30.154
indicating checkpoint inhibition alone is not sufficient

1673
01:37:30.294 --> 01:37:33.684
because the TME is not permissive to immune activity.

1674
01:37:37.414 --> 01:37:41.134
And today I will be introducing to you a monoclonal

1675
01:37:41.194 --> 01:37:45.054
antibody that could possibly be the key to solving this

1676
01:37:45.074 --> 01:37:45.474
problem.

1677
01:37:47.594 --> 01:37:50.674
So we decided to focus on a target called

1678
01:37:50.734 --> 01:37:54.714
TM4SF5. And what is TM4SF5? It is a

1679
01:37:54.794 --> 01:37:58.674
tetraspanin transmembrane protein overexpressed in

1680
01:37:58.734 --> 01:38:02.054
gastrointestinal cancers such as hepatocellular

1681
01:38:02.094 --> 01:38:05.974
carcinoma, colorectal cancer, and esophageal cancer.

1682
01:38:07.094 --> 01:38:10.794
But the important point is not only is it highly expressed in these

1683
01:38:10.854 --> 01:38:14.494
tumors, but it also plays a functional role in shaping the

1684
01:38:14.534 --> 01:38:16.964
immunosuppressive tumor microenvironment,

1685
01:38:17.894 --> 01:38:20.714
eventually leading to cancer progression and poor

1686
01:38:20.754 --> 01:38:22.434
prognosis overall.

1687
01:38:24.914 --> 01:38:28.714
And mechanistically, TM4SF5 contributes to such

1688
01:38:28.834 --> 01:38:32.754
tumor progression and immune evasion through signaling

1689
01:38:32.854 --> 01:38:36.842
interactions.So it acts as an anchor in a

1690
01:38:36.882 --> 01:38:39.342
microdomain we call term here.

1691
01:38:40.382 --> 01:38:43.972
TM4SF5 interacts with the IL-6 receptor to

1692
01:38:44.022 --> 01:38:47.482
enhance its STAT3 signaling, eventually

1693
01:38:47.522 --> 01:38:51.242
modulating T cell related cytokines and chemokines, and

1694
01:38:51.322 --> 01:38:55.212
also with SLAMF7 to induce its internalization and

1695
01:38:55.302 --> 01:38:58.642
degradation, leading to evasion of NK cell

1696
01:38:58.682 --> 01:38:59.402
recognition.

1697
01:39:00.362 --> 01:39:04.202
This makes TM4SF5 not just an expression marker,

1698
01:39:04.302 --> 01:39:08.162
but also a functional driver of the immunosuppressive TME.

1699
01:39:10.002 --> 01:39:13.562
Now, this biology is reflected in real

1700
01:39:13.662 --> 01:39:15.002
patient data as well.

1701
01:39:15.822 --> 01:39:19.812
When we stratify the patient data in public databases into

1702
01:39:20.002 --> 01:39:22.902
high and low TM4SF5 expression groups,

1703
01:39:23.702 --> 01:39:26.702
overall survival was found to be worse by about

1704
01:39:26.922 --> 01:39:30.102
twofold in the high expression group for both

1705
01:39:30.362 --> 01:39:32.002
HCC and CRC.

1706
01:39:33.002 --> 01:39:36.762
And through our collaboration with the National Cancer Center in Singapore,

1707
01:39:37.262 --> 01:39:40.862
we ran some RNA sequencing of HCC patient

1708
01:39:40.962 --> 01:39:44.902
samples, and we found that TM4SF5 expression

1709
01:39:44.942 --> 01:39:48.502
showed a positive correlation with immunosuppressive

1710
01:39:48.582 --> 01:39:52.332
genes and a negative correlation with those related

1711
01:39:52.382 --> 01:39:53.722
to immune activation.

1712
01:39:54.542 --> 01:39:58.462
And altogether, we were able to find that

1713
01:39:58.582 --> 01:40:01.422
high TM4SF5 expression can

1714
01:40:02.082 --> 01:40:05.962
identify with tumors that are potentially difficult to treat

1715
01:40:06.022 --> 01:40:09.082
with IO, pointing us in the direction of a

1716
01:40:09.122 --> 01:40:12.382
biomarker-driven therapeutic strategy.

1717
01:40:14.562 --> 01:40:18.342
Now, by this point, you might be wondering, if this is such a

1718
01:40:18.362 --> 01:40:21.002
great target, why has it not been developed before?

1719
01:40:21.122 --> 01:40:25.062
Why are we first in class? Well, the bottleneck is not

1720
01:40:25.122 --> 01:40:28.582
because the target itself is not attractive, but the

1721
01:40:28.622 --> 01:40:32.162
difficulty of effectively targeting this transmembrane

1722
01:40:32.242 --> 01:40:36.142
protein in its native conformation with the conventional methods

1723
01:40:36.542 --> 01:40:40.112
for antibody development. So to overcome this

1724
01:40:40.202 --> 01:40:44.042
challenge, we embedded TM4SF5 into a virus-like

1725
01:40:44.122 --> 01:40:47.902
lipoparticle in order to mimic its transmembrane-like

1726
01:40:48.042 --> 01:40:51.882
structure and use this to produce an extensive

1727
01:40:52.042 --> 01:40:55.892
antibody library. And so we were able to come up

1728
01:40:55.962 --> 01:40:59.522
with a monoclonal antibody that selectively recognizes the

1729
01:40:59.562 --> 01:41:03.442
conformational epitope of TM4SF5 in its

1730
01:41:03.452 --> 01:41:04.322
native structure.

1731
01:41:05.202 --> 01:41:06.262
And we

1732
01:41:07.402 --> 01:41:11.351
found a candidate antibody with excellent binding affinity and

1733
01:41:11.382 --> 01:41:14.322
further optimized it, and we call this

1734
01:41:15.022 --> 01:41:16.262
RCT1213.

1735
01:41:17.502 --> 01:41:21.302
Now, RCT1213 binds the conformational epitope,

1736
01:41:22.662 --> 01:41:25.702
spanning both extracellular loops of

1737
01:41:25.742 --> 01:41:29.622
TM4SF5. So I mentioned that it's a tetraspan, and so it

1738
01:41:29.822 --> 01:41:33.802
has two loops, EC1 and EC2. It

1739
01:41:33.812 --> 01:41:37.472
is very important that we are able to mask the entirety

1740
01:41:37.562 --> 01:41:41.452
of the loops because we found that only when

1741
01:41:41.462 --> 01:41:44.962
it binds across both of the loops can the antibody

1742
01:41:45.062 --> 01:41:48.882
disrupt the integrity of the microdomain in such a way that it

1743
01:41:48.942 --> 01:41:52.822
creates steric hindrance and weaken the immunosuppressive

1744
01:41:52.862 --> 01:41:55.882
effects that I outlined before.

1745
01:41:57.342 --> 01:42:01.222
As a result, we saw that IL-C receptor signaling and

1746
01:42:01.722 --> 01:42:04.982
downstream STAT3 activation were inhibited, and

1747
01:42:05.022 --> 01:42:08.872
disruption of SLAMF7 interactions restored

1748
01:42:09.522 --> 01:42:11.542
NK cell recognition on the tumor.

1749
01:42:12.532 --> 01:42:16.322
And we were able to see that RCT1213

1750
01:42:16.382 --> 01:42:20.262
effectively shifted the TME towards a more immune

1751
01:42:20.362 --> 01:42:21.182
permissive state

1752
01:42:22.022 --> 01:42:22.762
than before.

1753
01:42:25.282 --> 01:42:28.282
So we performed a series of characterization studies for

1754
01:42:28.382 --> 01:42:29.642
RCT1213.

1755
01:42:30.842 --> 01:42:34.582
We did a shotgun mutagenesis epitope mapping

1756
01:42:34.782 --> 01:42:38.302
of RCT1213 to confirm, yes,

1757
01:42:38.482 --> 01:42:42.122
that it binds to both the EC1 and

1758
01:42:42.182 --> 01:42:45.582
EC2 loops, and we saw excellent

1759
01:42:45.902 --> 01:42:48.042
binding specificity

1760
01:42:49.462 --> 01:42:53.201
in the cell lines that we tested. And also

1761
01:42:54.102 --> 01:42:57.802
in a biodistribution analysis of a tumor model, we saw that

1762
01:42:57.882 --> 01:43:01.342
RCT1213 targeted the tumor with minimal

1763
01:43:01.442 --> 01:43:04.222
off-target accumulation in normal organs.

1764
01:43:05.022 --> 01:43:08.482
And as a result of this targeting ability, we saw the

1765
01:43:08.522 --> 01:43:11.122
elicited immune responses that I mentioned.

1766
01:43:12.062 --> 01:43:16.022
We saw increased CD8 positive T cell population

1767
01:43:16.862 --> 01:43:20.402
in the tumor and also decreased Treg

1768
01:43:20.462 --> 01:43:21.302
proportions.

1769
01:43:22.482 --> 01:43:25.822
We also checked the suppression of immunosuppressive

1770
01:43:26.002 --> 01:43:29.542
cytokines and angiogenic factors, as well as

1771
01:43:29.622 --> 01:43:32.842
increase of immune activating factors such as

1772
01:43:32.862 --> 01:43:34.402
CXCL10.

1773
01:43:37.802 --> 01:43:40.602
Now the key question is whether

1774
01:43:41.402 --> 01:43:44.182
all of this translates into actual tumor control.

1775
01:43:44.262 --> 01:43:48.052
So we tested this in several in vivo models,

1776
01:43:48.162 --> 01:43:50.282
and we have two of them for you here today.

1777
01:43:51.082 --> 01:43:54.982
In the HCC model on the left and the MSS CRC model on

1778
01:43:55.042 --> 01:43:58.742
the right, we saw that RCT1213 achieved

1779
01:43:58.802 --> 01:44:01.402
significant tumor growth inhibition

1780
01:44:02.262 --> 01:44:03.702
of about 80%

1781
01:44:05.202 --> 01:44:09.082
at its max. This was comparable to a

1782
01:44:09.162 --> 01:44:12.682
leading first-line regimen, atezolizumab and bevacizumab

1783
01:44:13.162 --> 01:44:16.662
for HCC, and significantly better than

1784
01:44:16.682 --> 01:44:20.562
pembrolizumab in MSS CRC, which is known to

1785
01:44:20.602 --> 01:44:24.362
be largely not working in such

1786
01:44:25.142 --> 01:44:25.782
environment.

1787
01:44:26.702 --> 01:44:30.182
And what's particularly interesting is not only that we

1788
01:44:30.742 --> 01:44:33.702
see standalone efficacy, but in combination

1789
01:44:33.762 --> 01:44:37.754
settingsRCT1213 demonstrated clear synergy

1790
01:44:37.764 --> 01:44:40.984
with ICIs, with the triple combination of

1791
01:44:41.054 --> 01:44:44.634
RCT1213, atezolizumab, and bevacizumab

1792
01:44:45.134 --> 01:44:48.594
achieving complete response in all of our samples.

1793
01:44:49.594 --> 01:44:53.174
So collectively, we see that we're able to enhance

1794
01:44:53.214 --> 01:44:57.204
responsiveness to checkpoint inhibition in cancers that

1795
01:44:57.234 --> 01:45:00.294
are known to be difficult to treat with immunotherapy.

1796
01:45:01.754 --> 01:45:05.204
And we further validate this in a CRC PDX model

1797
01:45:05.334 --> 01:45:07.664
derived from a patient tumor sample,

1798
01:45:09.254 --> 01:45:11.664
known to have poor response to ICIs.

1799
01:45:12.354 --> 01:45:16.054
And RCT1213 demonstrated dose-dependent

1800
01:45:16.134 --> 01:45:19.934
tumor suppression in this case. And while not all

1801
01:45:20.054 --> 01:45:23.694
samples responded, as you can see in the waterfall plot on the

1802
01:45:23.774 --> 01:45:27.654
right, those that did showed substantial TGI

1803
01:45:27.774 --> 01:45:30.354
of about 60%.

1804
01:45:31.634 --> 01:45:35.474
And given we have not fully optimized the effective dose

1805
01:45:35.634 --> 01:45:39.513
in a patient-derived model, and that this

1806
01:45:39.614 --> 01:45:43.234
is a T cell deficient model, there is definitely room for

1807
01:45:43.294 --> 01:45:43.914
improvement,

1808
01:45:44.994 --> 01:45:46.854
which we are currently

1809
01:45:48.134 --> 01:45:49.674
conducting at this moment.

1810
01:45:50.474 --> 01:45:54.144
Nevertheless, we believe this data supports meaningful activity of

1811
01:45:54.234 --> 01:45:58.054
RCT1213 even in ICI refractory settings,

1812
01:45:58.634 --> 01:46:02.514
and studies are ongoing to continue

1813
01:46:02.554 --> 01:46:04.393
development in this direction.

1814
01:46:06.014 --> 01:46:09.474
Now to conclude, we are developing a highly selective

1815
01:46:09.514 --> 01:46:13.354
antibody with an immune-mediated MOA that helps to

1816
01:46:13.394 --> 01:46:16.914
reshape the immunosuppressive TME, also

1817
01:46:16.974 --> 01:46:20.214
enabling strong synergy with immune checkpoint blockade.

1818
01:46:20.954 --> 01:46:24.514
And we are pursuing a biomarker-driven strategy

1819
01:46:24.534 --> 01:46:28.304
using TM4SF5 expression for patient selection.

1820
01:46:29.834 --> 01:46:33.714
And with all this, we would assume the natural next step would be

1821
01:46:33.734 --> 01:46:37.534
to develop it into bispecific antibodies in order to

1822
01:46:37.614 --> 01:46:41.054
best leverage its excellent combination effect with the

1823
01:46:41.114 --> 01:46:41.814
ICIs.

1824
01:46:42.754 --> 01:46:46.694
And overall, while this is not a final product yet, I

1825
01:46:46.734 --> 01:46:50.294
believe this is a strong proof of concept for a

1826
01:46:50.394 --> 01:46:54.174
promising target, and we warmly welcome any discussions for

1827
01:46:54.274 --> 01:46:56.894
